        <name>3.4.1.7 Solve signal simultaneous</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A quadratic function \(y=ax^2+bx+c\) is used in signal processing to approximate a more complicated
signal. If this function must pass through the points with coordinates
\((0,0)\), \(({@c1@},{@c2@})\) and \(({@c3@},{@c4@})\) write down the simultaneous equations satisfied by \(a\), \(b\) and \(c\). Solve
these to find the quadratic function.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;\(y = \)&amp;nbsp;[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;The key to solving this problem is to notice that the curve passes through the point \((0, 0)\). This means that the value of \(c\) will &lt;i&gt;always&lt;/i&gt; be \(0\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This means that we only have to solve two equations in two unknowns to find the values of \(a\) and \(b\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For the point \(({@c1@},{@c2@})\) we get the equation \( {@c2@} = {@a*c1^2+b*c1@}.\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For the point \(({@c3@},{@c4@})\) we get the equation \( {@c4@} = {@a*c3^2+b*c3@}.\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We solve these equation simultenueslyand find \(a= {@aa@}\) and \(b= {@bb@} .\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hence, the quadratic equation is \[y = {@ta1@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
